##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "contextRationalFunction.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("RationalFunction-Strict");
$var1 = RandomVariableName(type=>'variable');
$var2 = $var1;
$var2 = RandomVariableName(type=>'variable') while($var2 eq $var1);
Context()->variables->are($var1=>'Real',$var2=>'Real');

#
#    (x^m y^n)^-p
#
# We choose m and n integer on [2,20] and p integer on [2,5].

# exponents
$m = random(3,15,1);
$n = random(3,15,1);
$p = random(2,5,1);

# total
$total1 = ($m*$p);
$total2 = ($n*$p);
$ans = Formula("$var1^($total1)/($var2^($total2))");

##############################################
TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML
Rewrite the expression simplified and using only positive exponents.

    [`
                \left([$var1]^{[$m*(-1)]}[$var2]^{[$n]}\right)^{[$p*(-1)]}=
     `][____________]{$ans}

[@KeyboardInstructions("Be careful to use grouping parenthesis appropriately. Remember that [|1/(2$var1)|]* is different from [|1/2$var1|]*.")@]**
END_PGML


BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

We use the properties of exponents to help us here, remembering that [``\frac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}``] and [`\left(a^m\right)^{n}=a^{mn}`]

    [`
           \begin{aligned}
                 \left([$var1]^{[$m*(-1)]}[$var2]^{[$n]}\right)^{[$p*(-1)]}
                      &= [$var1]^{([$m*(-1)])\cdot([$p*(-1)])}[$var2]^{[$n]\cdot([$p*(-1)])}\\
                      &= [$var1]^{[$m*(-1)*$p*(-1)]}[$var2]^{[$n*$p*(-1)]}\\
                                    & = [$ans]
           \end{aligned}
    `]

END_PGML_SOLUTION
##############################################


ENDDOCUMENT();
